== 歷史 ==
數位人文學的濫觴人文計算，可追溯至1940年代晚期耶穌會士Roberto Busa及其助手的研究成果<ref name="svensson">{{Cite journal|title=Humanities Computing as Digital Humanities|url=http://digitalhumanities.org/dhq/vol/3/3/000065/000065.html|last=Svensson|first=Patrik|journal=Digital Humanities Quarterly|accessdate=2012-05-30|issue=3|year=2009|volume=3|issn=1938-4122|archive-date=2021-01-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210116091442/http://digitalhumanities.org/dhq/vol/3/3/000065/000065.html|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name="hockney">{{Cite book|url=http://www.digitalhumanities.org/companion/view?docId=blackwell/9781405103213/9781405103213.xml&chunk.id=ss1-2-1&toc.depth=1&toc.id=ss1-2-1&brand=9781405103213_brand|title=Companion to Digital Humanities|last=Hockney|first=Susan|publisher=Blackwell|year=2004|isbn=1405103213|series=Blackwell Companions to Literature and Culture|location=Oxford|chapter=The History of Humanities Computing|editors=Susan Schreibman, Ray Siemens, John Unsworth (eds.)|access-date=2021-12-19|archive-date=2020-11-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201114003034/http://www.digitalhumanities.org/companion/view?docId=blackwell%2F9781405103213%2F9781405103213.xml&chunk.id=ss1-2-1&toc.depth=1&toc.id=ss1-2-1&brand=9781405103213_brand|dead-url=no}}</ref>。Rboerto Busa與[[IBM|IBM]]合作，利用電腦建立了[[托马斯·阿奎那|湯瑪斯・阿奎那]]著作的索引，稱為「Index Thornisticus」<ref name=":1" />。其他學者也開始使用[[大型主機|大型主機]]來自動化檢索、排序、計數等工作<ref name=":1" />。接下來的數十年，考古學者、歷史學者、古典學者、文學研究者等等，也開始採用電腦運算。<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Information Technology in Humanities Scholarship, British Achievements, Prospects, and Barriers|last2=Ross|first2=Seamus|journal=Historical Social Research|issue=1 (69)|year=1994|volume=19|pages=3–59|jstor=20755828|lastauthoramp=yes|last1=Feeney|first1=Mary}}</ref>

第一個專門期刊為1966年創刊的''Computers and the Humanities，''Association for Literary and Linguistic Computer (ALLC) 以及the Association for Computers and the Humanities (ACH)則分別在1977年與1978年成立。<ref name=":1" />

很快地，對數位文本標記規範的需求開始出現，首先發展的是Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) <ref name=":1" /> 。1987年，第一個TEI計畫開始，隨後於1994年5月第一版的''TEI Guidelines''出版<ref name="hockney" /> 。TEI 
形塑了電子文本的學術領域，並成為[[XML|XML]]的濫觴。研究者也開始嘗試使用資料庫與超文本編輯，與傳統線性的印刷不同，超文本相互連結的點和線組成<ref name=":1" />
1990年代，美國各人文計算研究中心已經建置了眾多的數位文本、影像資料庫（如女性作家計畫、[http://www.rossettiarchive.org/ 羅塞蒂檔案]<ref>{{Citation|title=Rossetti Archive|date=|url=http://www.rossettiarchive.org/|publisher=Institute for Advanced Technology in the Humanities, University of Virginia|editor=Jerome J. McGann|accessdate=2012-06-16}}</ref> 、{{link-en|威廉・布雷克檔案檔案|William_Blake_Archive}}等等）<ref>{{Citation|title=The William Blake Archive|date=|url=http://www.blakearchive.org/|publisher=|editors=Morris Eaves, Robert Essick, and Joseph Viscomi|accessdate=2012-06-16}}{{Dead link}}</ref>這些資料庫表現了文字編碼在文學資料上應用的成熟與穩健<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Transcendental Data: Toward a Cultural History and Aesthetics of the New Encoded Discourse|last=Liu|first=Alan|journal=Critical Inquiry|issue=1|doi=10.1086/427302|year=2004|volume=31|pages=49–84|issn=0093-1896|jstor=10.1086/427302}}</ref> 。個人電腦與全球資訊網的發展使得數位人文學得以往設計發展。全球資訊網的多媒體特性使得數位人文學工作得以整合音檔、影片等資料。<ref name=":1" />

從「人文計算」到「數位人文學」的用詞轉變，始於John Unsworth、Susan Schreibman、和Ray Siemens所編的文選<span>A </span>''Companion to Digital Humanities'' (2004)，該書試圖強調此領域並非「僅僅是數位化」<ref name="fitzpatrick">{{Cite news|url=http://chronicle.com/article/The-Humanities-Done-Digitally/127382/|title=The humanities, done digitally|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Kathleen|date=2011-05-08|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=2011-07-10|archive-date=2011-08-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828110016/http://chronicle.com/article/The-Humanities-Done-Digitally/127382|dead-url=no}}</ref>。「數位人文學」的提出，創造了兩個重疊的領域，即「以現代人文學方法來研究數位對象」<ref name="fitzpatrick" /> ，以及「在資訊科技方法來研究傳統人文問題」<ref name="fitzpatrick" /> 。個人電腦系統的使用與對電腦媒體的研究被稱為「電腦運算轉向」。<ref name="berry">{{Cite news|url=http://culturemachine.net/index.php/cm/article/viewDownloadInterstitial/440/470|title=The Computational Turn: Thinking About the Digital Humanities|last=Berry|first=David|date=2011-06-01|work=Culture Machine|accessdate=2012-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101152630/http://www.culturemachine.net/index.php/cm/article/viewDownloadInterstitial/440/470|archive-date=2012-01-01|dead-url=yes}}</ref>

2006年 National Endowment for the Humanities (NEH) 發起數位人文學倡議組織（2008年改名數位人文學辦公室），使得「數位人文學」一詞在美國被廣泛接受。<ref name="kirschenbaum-dept" />

數位人文學從上述的小眾議題發展為「大新聞<ref name="kirschenbaum-dept">{{Cite news|url=http://mkirschenbaum.files.wordpress.com/2011/01/kirschenbaum_ade150.pdf|title=What is Digital Humanities and What's it Doing in English Departments?|last=Kirschenbaum|first=Matthew G.|work=ADE Bulletin|accessdate=|year=2010|issue=150|volume=|archive-date=2020-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201204005041/https://mkirschenbaum.files.wordpress.com/2011/01/kirschenbaum_ade150.pdf|dead-url=no}}</ref>，2009年於[[費城|費城]]舉行的 [[美國現代語言學會|MLA convention]]中，數位人文學者被認為是「最可見的貢獻提供者之一」<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://chronicle.com/article/The-MLA-Convention-in/63379/|title=The MLA Convention in Translation|last=Howard|first=Jennifer|date=2009-12-31|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=2012-05-31|issn=0009-5982|archive-date=2012-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308132048/http://chronicle.com/article/The-MLA-Convention-in/63379/|dead-url=no}}</ref> ，其領域則被視為「下一個件大事」。<ref name="pannapacker-mla">{{Cite web|url=http://chronicle.com/blogPost/The-MLAthe-Digital/19468/|title=The MLA and the Digital Humanities|accessdate=2012-05-30|date=2009-12-28|last=Pannapacker|first=William|format=The Chronicle of Higher Education|work=Brainstorm|archive-date=2012-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514003204/http://chronicle.com/blogPost/The-MLAthe-Digital/19468/|dead-url=no}}</ref>

== 批判 ==
Lauren F. Klein與Matthew K. Gold整理了對數位人文學的批評：其一、缺乏對種族、階級、性別與性慾特質等議題的關注；其二、相較於教學取向的計畫，更重視研究取向的計畫；其三、缺乏對政治的投入；其四、參與者缺乏多樣性；其五、著作權問題；其六、資源的過度集中。<ref name="dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu">{{cite web|url=http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/debates/|title=Debates in the Digital Humanities|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421032743/http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/debates|archive-date=2019-04-21|dead-url=yes}}</ref>

'''負面宣傳'''

Klein and Gold note that many appearances of the digital humanities in public media are often in a critical fashion. Armand Leroi, writing in the [[纽约时报|New York Times]], discusses the contrast between the algorithmic analysis of themes in literary texts and the work of Harold Bloom, who qualitatively and phenomenologically analyzes the themes of literature over time. Leroi questions whether or not the digital humanities can provide a truly robust analysis of literature and social phenomenon or offer a novel alternative perspective on them. The literary theorist Stanley Fish claims that the digital humanities pursue a revolutionary agenda and thereby undermine the conventional standards of "pre-eminence, authority and disciplinary power."<ref name="fish-mortality">{{Cite news|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/09/the-digital-humanities-and-the-transcending-of-mortality/|title=The Digital Humanities and the Transcending of Mortality|last=Fish|first=Stanley|date=2012-01-09|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2012-05-30|location=New York|archive-date=2021-03-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210306084402/https://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/09/the-digital-humanities-and-the-transcending-of-mortality/|dead-url=no}}</ref>However, digital humanities scholars note that “Digital Humanities is an extension of traditional knowledge skills and methods, not a replacement for them. Its distinctive contributions do not obliterate the insights of the past, but add and supplement the humanities’ long-standing commitment to scholarly interpretation, informed research, structured argument, and dialogue within communities of practice”.<ref name=":1" />

有些倡議以數位人文學做為眼下人文面臨的各種問題的解方：即資金缺乏、反覆的辯論、以及對理論與方法論的不重視<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/14/opinion/digitizing-the-humanities.html|title=Digitizing the Humanities|accessdate=14 May 2016|publisher=The New York Times|last1=Leroi|first1=Armand|website=The New York Times Online|archive-date=2020-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108103827/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/14/opinion/digitizing-the-humanities.html|dead-url=no}}</ref> 。Adam Kirsch在''New Republic''中稱此為數位人文學「虛假的承諾」<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/117428/limits-digital-humanities-adam-kirsch|title=Technology Is Taking Over English Departments|accessdate=14 May 2016|publisher=The New Republic|last1=Kirsch|first1=Adam|website=The New Republic|archive-date=2021-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210308162028/https://newrepublic.com/article/117428/limits-digital-humanities-adam-kirsch|dead-url=no}}</ref> 。
在其他的人文學部門以及社會科學部門面臨資金的缺乏與聲譽的下降之際，數位人文學所得的資金與聲譽則正在增加。數位人文學在討論中通常被視為革命性的替代方法，或只是舊瓶裝新酒。Kirsch認為數位人文學的參與者面臨的困難，在於推銷做得比研究多，這些工作只是在證實研究方法的能力，而非真的進行分析。就算是做了分析，也只是做些嘩眾取寵的內容而已。這類的批評也有其他學者提出，如Carl Staumshein即在''Inside Higher Education''中稱之為「數位人文學泡沫」<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/05/08/digital-humanities-wont-save-humanities-digital-humanists-say|title=Digital Humanities Bubble|accessdate=14 May 2016|publisher=Inside Higher Education|last1=Straumshein|first1=Carl|archive-date=2020-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200901172243/https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/05/08/digital-humanities-wont-save-humanities-digital-humanists-say|dead-url=no}}</ref>；Straumshein則指控數位人文學是人文學「社團主義的重組」<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2016/05/06/article-criticizes-impact-digital-humanities-colleges|title=Digital Humanities as 'Corporatist Restructuring'|accessdate=14 May 2016|publisher=Inside Higher Education|last1=Straumshein|first1=Carl|website=Inside Higher Education|archive-date=2021-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210124141739/https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2016/05/06/article-criticizes-impact-digital-humanities-colleges|dead-url=no}}</ref> 。一些人認為數位人文學與商業的結盟對人文學來說是個好的轉變，因為若能提高業界對人文學的重視，增加對人文學研究的資助<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2016/04/24/humanities-and-business-hand-hand/9nG9n04SSF1Ko0MRJjguxK/story.html|title=Humanities and business go hand in hand|accessdate=14 May 2016|publisher=The Boston Globe|last1=Carlson|first1=Tracy|archive-date=2021-01-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117102033/https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2016/04/24/humanities-and-business-hand-hand/9nG9n04SSF1Ko0MRJjguxK/story.html|dead-url=no}}</ref> 。若不是「數位人文學」這個名字的包袱，這些計畫所獲得的資助是不公平的。<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chronicle.com/article/Stop-Calling-It-Digital/137325/|title=Stop Calling It 'Digital Humanities'|accessdate=14 May 2016|publisher=Chronicle of Higher Education|last1=Pannapacker|first1=William|archive-date=2021-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210304040033/http://www.chronicle.com/article/Stop-Calling-It-Digital/137325/|dead-url=no}}</ref>

'''「黑箱」'''

不清楚數位人文工具原理的學者對工具的過度信任，他們將資料放入這個「黑箱」裡頭，不清楚中間發生了什麼事，也不知道如何檢驗錯誤。[[洛杉磯加大|洛杉磯加大]]資訊科學系教授Johanna Drucker稱此為「認識論的謬誤」，並認為這普遍出現在熱門的視覺化工具與科技，如網絡圖與主題模型工具對人文學工作來說仍過度粗糙<ref name="vimeo.com">{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/140307034|title=Johanna Drucker (UCLA) Lecture, "Should Humanists Visualize Knowledge?"|website=Vimeo|access-date=2016-01-25|archive-date=2019-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416221135/https://vimeo.com/140307034|dead-url=no}}</ref>。

'''多樣性'''

另外也有對數位人文學參與者多樣性爭議的討論，Tara McPherson將數位人文學中種族多樣性的缺乏歸因於[[UNIX|UNIX]]與電腦的模式<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/debates/text/29|title=Debates in the Digital Humanities|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-17|archive-date=2019-07-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706154943/http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/debates/text/29|dead-url=no}}</ref> 。DHpoco.org上的一個開放的線程最近收集了關於數位人文學科種族問題的100多條評論，學者爭論了種族（及其他） 偏見對數位人文學者所使用的工具、文本的影響<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhpoco.org/blog/2013/05/10/open-thread-the-digital-humanities-as-a-historical-refuge-from-raceclassgendersexualitydisability/|title=Open Thread: The Digital Humanities as a Historical "Refuge" from Race/Class/Gender/Sexuality/Disability?|publisher=|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203021953/http://dhpoco.org/blog/2013/05/10/open-thread-the-digital-humanities-as-a-historical-refuge-from-raceclassgendersexualitydisability/|archivedate=2013-12-03}}</ref> 。McPherson認為需要理解即使分析的主題不是關於種族，也需要理解、理論化資訊技術對種族的影響。 

Amy E. Earheart批評了在文本獲取計畫中，從使用簡單的HTML的網站，轉向使用TEI和視覺化，形成了數位人文學的新的「典範」。<ref name="ReferenceB">{{Cite web |url=http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/debates/text/16 |title=存档副本 |access-date=2017-01-17 |archive-date=2019-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718214106/http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/debates/text/16 |dead-url=no }}</ref> 先前已經遺失或被排除的作品，現在可以網路上找到新家，但在傳統人文學中被邊緣化的作品，在網路上往往也被邊緣化。根據Earhart的說法，「我們做為數位人文學者，
有需要對目前我們正建立的這個典範展開檢驗，因為這個典範正傾向傳統文本，而排除了婦女、有色人種與GLBTQ社群。<ref name="ReferenceB" />

'''存取問題'''

Practitioners in digital humanities are also failing to meet the needs of users with disabilities. George H. Williams argues that universal design is imperative for practitioners to increase usability because "many of the otherwise most valuable digital resources are useless for people who are—for example—deaf or hard of hearing, as well as for people who are blind, have low vision, or have difficulty distinguishing particular colors." <ref name="ReferenceC">{{Cite web |url=http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/debates/text/44 |title=存档副本 |access-date=2017-01-17 |archive-date=2019-07-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706214341/http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/debates/text/44 |dead-url=no }}</ref>In order to provide accessibility successfully, and productive universal design, it is important to understand why and how users with disabilities are using the digital resources while remembering that all users approach their informational needs differently.<ref name="ReferenceC" />

'''文化批判'''

數位人文學一直以來被批評不僅忽視傳統的人文學問題的系譜與歷史，也缺乏做為人文學基礎的文化批判。然而人文學是否必須與文化批判連結才是人文學仍是問題<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liu.english.ucsb.edu/where-is-cultural-criticism-in-the-digital-humanities/|title=Where is Cultural Criticism in the Digital Humanities?|accessdate=14 May 2016|publisher=UCSB|last1=Liu|first1=Alan|archive-date=2020-11-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201114001338/https://liu.english.ucsb.edu/where-is-cultural-criticism-in-the-digital-humanities/|dead-url=no}}</ref> 。科學視數位人文學為自非量化方法的進步。<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v474/n7352/full/474420b.html|title='Poetry in Motion'|accessdate=14 May 2016|publisher=Nature|website=Nature|archive-date=2016-07-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727171237/http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v474/n7352/full/474420b.html|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mkirschenbaum.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/dhterriblethingskirschenbaum.pdf|title=What Is "Digital Humanities," and Why Are They Saying Such Terrible Things about It?|accessdate=14 May 2016|publisher=Matthew Kirschenbaum|last1=Kirschenbaum|first1=Matthew|website=Wordpress|archive-date=2020-08-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200823053625/https://mkirschenbaum.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/dhterriblethingskirschenbaum.pdf|dead-url=no}}</ref>

'''評價的困難'''

隨著此一領域逐漸成熟，學者們開始認識到既有學術同儕審查的標準模型，對數位人文學來說可能不適合，因為其計畫通常包括網站、資料庫等非印刷的內容。因此評價需要新舊混合的方法<ref name=":1" /> 。對此問題的回應之一，是''[https://web.archive.org/web/20150905134109/http://dhcommons.org/journal DHCommons Journal]''的設立，該期刊接受非傳統的投稿，特別是在計畫中程的數位人文學計畫，並提供較適合多媒體、跨學科、多階段性的數位人文學計畫的創新同儕審查方式。

'''對教學法缺乏關注'''

2012年版的 ''[http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/ Debates in the Digital Humanities] {{Wayback|url=http://dhdebates.gc.cuny.edu/ |date=20210211211025 }}''提出在教學法在數位人文學中是「被忽視的繼子」並加了一章討論數位人文學教學<ref name=":3" />。這個問題的成因之一，是贊助主要集中在能提供量化成果的研究而非難以評估的教學創<ref name=":3" /> 。體認到此一領域教學的需要，''[http://books.openedition.org/obp/1605 Digital Humanities Pedagogy] {{Wayback|url=http://books.openedition.org/obp/1605 |date=20191130181147 }}'' 提供了案例研究與在各領域如何教導數位人文學的策略。

== 組織 ==
The Alliance of Digital Humanities Organizations (ADHO) is an umbrella organization that supports digital research and teaching as a consultative and advisory force for its constituent organizations. Its governance was approved in 2005 and it has overseen the annual Digital Humanities conference since 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adho.org/about|title=About {{!}} ADHO|website=adho.org|access-date=2016-12-26|archive-date=2017-02-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206055336/http://www.adho.org/about|dead-url=no}}</ref>The current members of ADHO are:
* Australasian Association for Digital Humanities (aaDH)
* Association for Computers and the Humanities (ACH)
* Canadian Society for Digital Humanities / Société canadienne des humanités numériques (CSDH/SCHN)
* [https://dhcenternet.org/ centerNet] {{Wayback|url=https://dhcenternet.org/ |date=20210322125618 }}, an international network of digital humanities centers
* The European Association for Digital Humanities (EADH)
* Japanese Association for Digital Humanities (JADH)
* Humanistica, L'association francophone des humanités numériques/digitales (Humanistica)
* [http://www.tadh.org.tw Taiwanese Association for Digital Humanities] {{Wayback|url=http://www.tadh.org.tw/ |date=20201127225217 }}(TADH) [http://www.tadh.org.tw 臺灣數位人文學會] {{Wayback|url=http://www.tadh.org.tw/ |date=20201127225217 }}

ADHO funds a number of projects such as the Digital Humanities Quarterly journal and the Digital Scholarship in the Humanities (DSH) journal, supports the Text Encoding Initiative, and sponsors workshops and conferences, as well as funding small projects, awards, and bursaries.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Editorial|url=http://llc.oxfordjournals.org/content/26/1/3.short|last=Vanhoutte|first=Edward|date=2011-04-01|journal=Literary and Linguistic Computing|accessdate=2011-07-11|issue=1|doi=10.1093/llc/fqr002|volume=26|pages=3–4|archive-date=2013-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216043141/http://llc.oxfordjournals.org/content/26/1/3.short|dead-url=no}}</ref>

HASTAC (Humanities, Arts, Science, and Technology Alliance and Collaboratory) is a free and open access virtual, interdisciplinary community focused on changing teaching and learning through the sharing of news, tools, methods, and pedagogy, including digital humanities scholarship.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hastac.org/about-hastac|title=About HASTAC|newspaper=HASTAC|access-date=2016-12-26|archive-date=2021-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310073633/https://www.hastac.org/about-hastac|dead-url=no}}</ref>It is reputed to be the world's first and oldest academic social network.<ref name=":2" />

